On the plate that is connected to the motherboard are arrows pointing to screws. Remove these screws. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7c/Pic16.jpg/460px-Pic16.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/7/7c/Pic16.jpg/728px-Pic16.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Four more screws attach two plates to the motherboard. Remove these screws as well and set the plates aside. Be careful from here on out, as the plate will not be attached to the motherboard directly. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/39/Pic17.jpg/460px-Pic17.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/3/39/Pic17.jpg/728px-Pic17.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Unscrew the ground wire from the frame. Now gently pull the back plate away from the main unit and set it aside. Flip the unit over and you will see a little green battery attached to the bottom plate. Unplug this from the motherboard that is underneath. Opposite the battery is the plug-in for the fan running into the motherboard. Unplug this as well. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/f\/f1\/Pic23.jpg\/460px-Pic23.jpg","bigUrl":"\/images\/thumb\/f\/f1\/Pic23.jpg\/728px-Pic23.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

The HD bay can be seen jutting out from the bottom of the bottom plate. Unscrew this and set it aside. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/3\/30\/Pic25.jpg\/460px-Pic25.jpg","bigUrl":"\/images\/thumb\/3\/30\/Pic25.jpg\/728px-Pic25.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

The ports for the inputs are attached to the bottom assembly as well. Go ahead and remove those and set them aside. The bottom plate should now lift away from the motherboard and take the fan and heat sinks with it. Set it down with the fans on the top side as you will be working on it shortly.

You can now see your CPU and GPU (the two big squares in the center of the motherboard) with the old thermal paste on them. Using a paper towel gently rub the paste off of their surface, being careful not to scratch them.Before:{"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f2/Pic28.jpg/460px-Pic28.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/f/f2/Pic28.jpg/728px-Pic28.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

